               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1325" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1325" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1325" type="surname" value="HAYDON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1325" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN HAYDON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a linen-draper, of 51, Bermondsey-street. On 24th Oct., about half-past seven o'clock in the morning, I placed this piece of cotton on a rail inside my doorway—I missed it about ten minutes past eleven—it has my private mark on it, and has not been sold—I told the police, and the prisoner was brought in about an hour—I went to the station, and found the print in three pieces.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18481023-name-1326" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1326" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1326" type="surname" value="AYLETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18481023-name-1326" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>ALFRED AYLETT</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman</hi>). I received information, and on 24th Oct., about twelve o'clock, took a pattern of the print, and saw a female offering a piece to pledge at a pawnbroker's in High-street—she said it was given her by her sister—I took her to the station—she gave me information, and I found the prisoner at 8, Red Cross-street, Borough—I said her sister was in custody for stealing some print—she said she knew nothing about it; then she said a woman gave it her, and she gave part of it to her sister to pledge, and the remainder was at home—I went there and found two more pieces—they all corresponded.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> A woman with a baby asked me to hold a bundle while she went into a shop; she did not return, and I took it home.</p>
               <p>
